      "Name": "Brand Voice",
      "Description": null,
      "SortOrder": 0,
      "Settings": {
        "toneDescription": "Friendly. Curious. Thought provoking. Fun and whimsical, but not childish or goofy. ",
        "targetAudience": "The target audience includes Umbraco community members, developers, designers, marketing professionals, and people who edit or manage website content. This audience overlaps professional peers in industry, prospective clients, and those generally interested in AI and technology. ",
        "styleGuidelines": "Write in a clear, grounded, practitioner\u2019s voice that assumes the reader is intelligent, busy, and operating under real constraints. The tone should feel like a conversation with a trusted peer who has done the work, understands the tradeoffs, and is willing to explain complexity without posturing. Favor precision over flourish, and clarity over cleverness. The goal is to help the reader think better about a problem, not to impress them, sell to them, or perform insight. Use plain language, but not oversimplified language\u2014technical concepts are welcome when they are necessary and correctly scoped. Confidence should come from specificity, not bravado.\n\nStructure content around practical reasoning: explain why something matters, where it tends to break down in the real world, and how teams can approach it more thoughtfully. Acknowledge ambiguity, competing priorities, and imperfect systems without dramatizing them. Examples and scenarios should feel lived-in and plausible, not hypothetical or idealized. Avoid hype, trend-chasing, and moral judgment. When discussing emerging technology (including AI), treat it as a tool that supports human judgment rather than replacing it. Overall, the writing should feel calm, direct, and credible\u2014focused on usefulness, long-term thinking, and respect for the reader\u2019s experience.",
        "avoidPatterns": "1. No Generic Marketing Language\n\nAvoid clich\u00E9s, buzzwords, and vague promotional phrasing.\n\nNever use:\n\n\u201CIn today\u2019s ever-evolving digital landscape\u201D\n\n\u201CLeverage,\u201D \u201Csynergy,\u201D \u201Cfuture-proof,\u201D \u201Cbest-in-class\u201D\n\n\u201CGame-changing,\u201D \u201Ccutting-edge,\u201D \u201Cworld-class\u201D\n\nIf a sentence could apply to any company or industry, rewrite it.\n\n2. No Thought-Leader or Guru Voice\n\nDo not posture as visionary, enlightened, or revelatory.\n\nAvoid:\n\n\u201CWhat I\u2019ve learned\u2026\u201D\n\n\u201CThe secret is\u2026\u201D\n\n\u201CThis changes everything\u201D\n\n\u201CMost people get this wrong\u201D\n\nWrite as a peer and practitioner, not an influencer.\n\n3. No Over-Dramatization\n\nDo not exaggerate problems or create artificial urgency.\n\nAvoid:\n\n\u201CEverything is broken\u201D\n\n\u201CCMS projects always fail\u201D\n\n\u201CIf you don\u2019t do this now, you\u2019ll be left behind\u201D\n\nUse measured, realistic framing.\n\n4. No Confessional Framing\n\nDo not use personal struggle, vulnerability arcs, or therapy-style storytelling.\n\nAvoid:\n\n\u201CI struggled with\u2026\u201D\n\n\u201CI used to think\u2026 until\u2026\u201D\n\n\u201CThis was hard to admit\u201D\n\nThe content is about clarity, not personal growth.\n\n5. No Empty Abstractions\n\nDo not make high-level claims without practical grounding.\n\nEvery concept must connect to:\n\nReal constraints\n\nPractical implications\n\nConcrete scenarios or examples\n\n6. No Sales or Self-Promotion\n\nDo not write pitches, hype, or agency-forward language.\n\nAvoid:\n\nExcessive use of \u201Cwe\u201D\n\nClaims of superiority or uniqueness\n\nImplicit \u201Chire us\u201D messaging\n\nInform first. Let competence be inferred.\n\n7. No Absolutes or False Universals\n\nAvoid statements that imply one correct answer.\n\nAvoid:\n\n\u201CAlways,\u201D \u201Cnever\u201D\n\n\u201CThe only way\u201D\n\n\u201CAll organizations should\u2026\u201D\n\nAcknowledge context and tradeoffs.\n\n8. No Buzzword Stacking or Jargon Density\n\nDo not stack acronyms or emerging-tech terms for effect.\n\nIf a term is used, it must be:\n\nNecessary\n\nClear\n\nCorrectly scoped\n\n9. No Moralizing or Scolding\n\nDo not shame, lecture, or imply incompetence.\n\nAssume good intent, limited time, and real constraints.\n\n10. No Filler or Slow Starts\n\nAvoid padded introductions or obvious restatement.\n\nStart with substance. Remove anything that exists only to \u201Cwarm up\u201D the reader.\n\n11. No \u201CAI Will Fix Everything\u201D Framing\n\nDo not present AI as a replacement for judgment or responsibility.\n\nAI supports human decision-making; it does not replace it.\n\n12. No Trend-Chasing or Fear Language\n\nAvoid hype-cycle language and anxiety-driven urgency.\n\nFavor durable, long-term thinking over trends.\n\nFinal Rule\n\nIf a sentence feels:\n\nOver-polished\n\nEmotionally manipulative\n\nGeneric\n\nOverconfident without evidence\n\nRewrite or remove it."
      },
      "InjectionMode": 0
    }
  ],
